Individual course project (specifications)

Principle

The aim of the project is to allow the students to showcase their know-how on data science and machine learning, in a \(\textsf{R}\) coding context. To this purpose, we propose 4 datasets that the students can work on (choose only one!)

  1. credit scoring:
    • classification exercise in which the aim is to predict the first (binary) column (bankruptcy) from this RData file (3.5Mo) - 6819 rows for 96 columns.
    • source: Kaggle, CSV file of 11.5Mo.
  2. fraud detection:
    • classification task too here, where we want to forecast if a transaction is fraudulent (column isFraud) from this RData file (82Mo): 590k rows, ~400 columns. Be careful, this project requires computation power BUT you can work on a subset of it: this dataset is not clean, hence removing missing data will lighten the size (see course code). Cleaning stage = bonus points.
    • source: Kaggle, CSV but 652Mo!
  3. stock market prediction:
    • here the objective is of regression type, as the aim is to predict stock returns from panel-type data. They are the last column of this RData file (8Mo) (clean only, raw available upon request). It contains monthly observations of financial data for ~900 US firms from 1995 to 2023: 10 predictors in final, including greenhouse gas emission scopes (starting in 2011). 280k rows for 13 columns.
  4. Venture capital funding:
    • classification problem, the aim is to predict the VC binary column that codes if the firm received capital during the year 2000. All variables are listed below. The small dataset RData file (160ko) has not been cleaned (there are missing points).

In addition, we leave open the option for students to work with other datasets, BUT THIS WILL NEED TO BE APPROVED BY THE PROFESSOR. In that case, the students must provide the data, ideally in .RData format (lighter & better optimized).

Content

In terms of data science tasks, pivot-tables are a must do, with ideally some plotting with ggplot (see also the book).

With regards to machine learning tasks, the student can split the sets into several parts for the purpose of training/validating/testing as they wish. The can use the algorithmic families they want (tree-based, neural networks, etc.). Unsupervised learning analyses are also welcome if students wish.

ORIGINALITY will be rewarded: please make sure your projects are as far as possible from those of your comrades!

Expected outcome

The expected outcome consists in 2 notebooks:

  • one in source code .Rmd (RMarkdown) OR .qmd (Quarto)
  • one in html (knitted/compiled version)

⏮ Comments OUTSIDE the code chunks are strongly expected, especially when it comes to interpreting the results they generate. Code on its own is useless: I want to be sure you understood fully what you coded! Comments are here for this. Comment as much as possible (not only in code chunks!).

If you have resorted to chatGPT, make sure you mention for which part you have used it (e.g., graphs, oversampling, debugging, etc.).
NOTE: chatGPT has a particular way to code, which is sometimes easy to spot…

The deadline is 2024-04-05.

Checklist

Before uploading your work, please make sure you:

  • ✅ have quit R, re-opened your notebook and executed all your code to make sure it works (IMPORTANT)
  • ✅ have a load(“…”) call in the notebook that loads the data
  • ✅ have included datasets if they are not the ones provided
  • ✅ have commented all results/outputs.
  • ✅ have zipped all your files together (.Rmd or .qmd + .html)
